            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Matthew Peterson\u2019s life began far from the fog-laced hills of San Francisco, in the predictable suburbs of Columbus, Ohio. The son of a pragmatic engineer and a nurturing high school teacher, his upbringing was stable, comfortable, and instilled in him a powerful work ethic. He followed a safe path through Ohio State, but a growing restlessness led him to seek a more dynamic future. The Berkeley Haas School of Business was his calculated escape hatch, a ticket to the burgeoning tech world of the late 1990s.\n\nHe graduated with his MBA directly into the chaos of the dot-com bust, a sobering lesson that tempered his ambition with a dose of caution. While his peers chased fleeting startup glory, Matthew opted for a role at a more established medical technology firm. It was a slower, more deliberate climb, but it was secure. Over two decades, he methodically rose through the ranks, his talent for translating complex scientific concepts into marketable products making him invaluable. His career flourished, but his personal life fractured; a marriage, forged in the optimism of his MBA years, buckled under the weight of 12-hour workdays and divergent life goals, ending in an amicable but lonely divorce five years ago.\n\nNow, at 49, Matthew is a Director of Product Management, a respected figure in his field. His life runs on a disciplined schedule. Mornings start with the gray light filtering into his tidy Noe Valley flat, followed by a quick espresso before his rideshare arrives for the 3.5-mile trip to his SoMa office. His days are a marathon of strategic meetings and team management, a world of roadmaps and revenue projections.\n\nHe\u2019s a settled San Franciscan, appreciating the city\u2019s culinary scene and the easy access to hiking in Marin on weekends. His social circle is small and consists mainly of colleagues and other professionals his age. Having achieved the financial and professional success he once craved, Matthew\u2019s aspirations have shifted inward. He hopes to find a relationship built on more than shared ambition and dreams of a \"second act\" career\u2014perhaps consulting for non-profits or mentoring young entrepreneurs\u2014where his impact feels more personal and less tied to a balance sheet."
        },
