            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the specific weight of the Berkeley Haas acceptance letter in his hands, heavier than just paper on a gray Columbus afternoon. The golden bear on the letterhead was a silent promise of a world beyond predictable Ohio horizons. It wasn\u2019t just an admission; it felt like a getaway car. That single piece of paper, arriving in the mid-90s, solidified his decision to chase not just a career, but an entirely different version of his life\u2014one he believed would be drenched in California sun and endless possibility.\n\n2.\nIn 2001, just a year out of business school, he\u2019d walk through SoMa past the hollowed-out offices, the \u201cFor Lease\u201d signs multiplying like a virus. The air, once electric with IPO chatter, was thick with the dust of failure. It was a sobering, silent lesson in risk. While his peers scrambled for the next big thing, the bust bolted a layer of his father's pragmatism onto his own ambition. It directly led him to the safer, more deliberate path of medical technology, a decision that would define the next two decades.\n\n3.\nThey were at a celebrated restaurant in the Mission about seven years ago, a reservation he\u2019d secured weeks in advance. His then-wife was detailing a funding round for her startup, her eyes ablaze with strategic fire. He tried to share a breakthrough with a new cardiac device, but saw her gaze drift past him. He starkly realized they were just two CEOs of parallel companies, not partners sharing a life. The exquisite food tasted like ash, teaching him that shared ambition could be a hollow foundation for love.\n\n4.\nTwo years ago, standing alone on a trail high on Mount Tamalpais, Matthew looked across the bay. The city gleamed, a collection of towers he had, in his own way, helped build. He had the view, the career, the financial security\u2014everything his younger self had run from Ohio to find. But the achievement felt strangely empty, a beautiful, distant vista. The profound loneliness of that moment clarified his new goal: to build an inner life with a view that was just as rewarding as the one from the mountain.\n\n5.\nLast fall, a barista at his Noe Valley coffee shop asked for advice. Her friend was building an app to connect seniors with caregivers and was stuck. Matthew spent twenty minutes sketching a product roadmap on a napkin, translating her passion into actionable steps. Seeing the clarity spark in her eyes gave him a jolt of satisfaction more potent than any quarterly review. It was the first concrete glimpse of his desired \"second act\"\u2014one measured not in revenue, but in ripples of genuine human impact."
